            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers his first team lunch, just 23 and eager to impress. The manager, trying to be inclusive, saw \"Malhotra\" on the roster and asked excitedly if he knew the best new biryani spot. A familiar heat crept up his neck. He gave his practiced, gentle smile, explaining his mom\u2019s Irish cooking was more his speed. It wasn\u2019t malice, just a reminder he was a walking puzzle. The moment cemented his habit of preemptively owning the story, turning a potential speedbump of identity into a simple, smooth introduction.\n\n2.\nHe was 21, standing on a metal catwalk during his Cal Poly internship. Below, forklifts moved in new, fluid paths he\u2019d designed only weeks before on a screen. The chaotic buzz he\u2019d first seen was gone, replaced by a quiet, purposeful hum. It was the first time an idea in his head had reshaped the physical world. A deep, electric thrill shot through him\u2014this was it. This was what he was meant to do. He wasn't just optimizing; he was creating order from noise.\n\n3.\nAt 23, his first night in the Mission was a symphony of chaos. Boxes formed mountains in the living room he shared with two strangers. Through the thin window, he heard sirens, laughter from a taqueria, and the rumble of a skateboard. Lying on an air mattress, he felt a powerful surge of independence tinged with fear. Fremont was gone. This noisy, vibrant, demanding place was his now. It was the thrill of the starting line, the first concrete step toward the life he\u2019d meticulously planned.\n\n4.\nSix months into his job, he was crammed into a booth at a dim bar for trivia night. He felt a pang of loneliness, still the new guy. Then the final question came: something obscure about 90s manufacturing processes. His niche. He blurted out the answer, and their team won by a single point. The explosion of cheers from his work-friends, the sloshing of a shared pitcher\u2014that felt more validating than any performance review. That night, he wasn\u2019t just a colleague; he was finally part of the team.\n\n5.\nJust last month, walking the factory floor, he saw the final packaging for a batch of cardiovascular stents. His process change had shaved seven precious minutes off the assembly of a crucial component inside. He watched a box get sealed, marked for a hospital in Ohio. For a moment, it wasn't about cycle times or cost savings. It was a person\u2019s life, a family\u2019s hope, in that box. The thought was humbling, connecting his spreadsheets to a human heartbeat and making his grander ambitions feel suddenly real."
